CEO @AliFiddy said the report "completely misses the point" 

"The Tribunal doesn‚Äôt uphold parents' appeals because they engage persuasive advocates or because the judge gives in to demanding families ‚Äì decisions are made on the basis of law and evidence"
Unsurprisingly, it's met with concern among organisations who help parents and carers navigate the SEN process, including @IPSEAcharity

There's more, a lot more. But it's all along the same lines: councils aren't losing almost every tribunal because they're making wrong decisions, it's the system itself that's wrong. And it feels like a report commissioned to find exactly that

Either way, the report goes onto admit that it (again) has no evidence - beyond the views of few council leaders - to support its claims because ethnicity and class data of families appealing to the tribunal is not collected

Is this concern about disadvantaged and ethnic minority families being excluded (a real problem, as with any similar process) or a pretty crude attempt to undermine the validity of the tribunal's decisions by questioning the equity of the process as a whole?

Worse still, the report leans heavily the idea of a system being abused by the middle classes. It quotes the view of a single council leader: "If [the dispute resolution system] is set up to allow the white middle-class population to challenge LA decisions, what is the point?‚Äô

Besides, the reports insists its concerns are not with parents seeking legal advice but "a potential trend of families being encouraged to seek the resolution of appeals through judicial means"

Right. 

Either way, isn't that advice fair if 96% of decisions go in their way?

They said "local leaders" and "national bodies" had described such organisations as an "industry" which had grown rapidly. 

Before later admitting they had no hard evidence to support these claims.

Instead the report bemoans the growth of so-called "advocacy organisations" which its researchers had been told (by councils and government) were "encouraging appeals, discouraging mediation and making claims about helping families to win Tribunals, in return for payment"

Quite rightly the report acknowledges that the system has become more "adversarial". But it makes little attempt to scrutinise councils' role in contributing to a process which in which all sides feel pitched against the others
More to say but I'm due in a meeting

I've been speaking to people involved in all parts of the SEN system and its hard to imagine a report that better embodies the resentment felt by many local authority staff, and the fears of those trying to secure support for their children

Instead it such figures are indication of a system where "something very significant is not working as it should" 

Which is right, in a sense. Local authority decision-making is not working as it should. It's found to be unlawful in nine out of ten cases
The report acknowledges but completely brushes over the fact that a second crucial avenue of accountability is also ruling against councils time and time again

But there were a few points that jumped out at me. Firstly, that it's not just the first-tier tribunal coming down in favour of parents. It's also the Ombudsman, which upheld an unprecedented 89% of SEND complaints in 2020-21

There people far better placed than me to pick apart the report's attempts to absolve local authorities of almost all blame, to argue that councils lose almost every case not because they take decisions that contravene the law but due to circumstances beyond their control

In this report @IsosPartnership claims otherwise, arguing the figures are instead "symptomatic of fundamental imbalances in the SEND system" -  issues that local authorities are far more victim of than perpetrator

In 2020/21, 96% appeals to the tribunal - which rules on whether the law has been applied - were successful. It's a staggering figure and one which families, campaigners and charities say is indicative of systemic unlawful decisions taken by councils

Parents have the right to appeal to the first-tier tribunal if they disagree with decisions relating to their child including a council refusing to carry out an assessment of need or to issue a plan for how their needs will be met (called an EHCP)

A quite extraordinary report commissioned by the Local Government Association (@LGAcomms) which argues that councils losing a very high % of SEN tribunals is not evidence of widespread unlawful decision making https://t.co/dX4VwBUPXx

@ByRobDavies Like you say, there's no easy answer. But are the rules around sources so sacrosanct, the public interest in stories like this so overriding, that we are comfortable with being used by people for their own personal gain?

@ByRobDavies But I'd make clear that, in this reply, I'm talking about leaks and political reporting generally. Clearly there may be specific circumstances with these stories where identification is more likely

@ByRobDavies I think you can't accurately publish something like this without in some way acknowledging where it came from, and I think you can do it without identifying specific individuals. I think it doesn't happen as much out of fear of not getting more tips as it does protecting sources
The unwritten and sacrosanct rules of the journalist-source relationship don't stop other reporters from asking who's doing the leaking and why.

Furthermore, if the assumption everyone is making is correct - that figures within government, perhaps very senior ones, are attempting to bring down the Prime Minister by leaking incriminating stories to the media - couldn't you argue that's a bigger story than the parties?

@glennebrey Pretty obvious to you as a journalist making an educated guess. But what about the general reader? Even if we're all part of a charade where everyone knows the who and why and just goes along with it anyway, is that right?

But it goes beyond that. There seems, repeatedly, to be little to no appetite to question the motivation of sources and for that motivation to be factored into reporting. And not just in a public facing way. Are these questions being asked in newsrooms before publication?

While not unique to it, this does seem a particular issue with political reporting. Sources benefit from leaking to the press, at times which suit them, and journalists benefit from those leaks. There's an obvious reluctance to bite the hand that feeds
It's tricky because of course there's a clear public interest in this stuff coming out. But that doesn't, imo, override the important consideration of the motivation behind it

This info, and the supporting photographs/videos, have been kept back, in some cases for a year, in order to do as much political damage as possible. The media is, essentially, being (willingly) used to make sure that happens

Two questions that appear to be missing, by and large, from coverage of the Conservative Christmas Parties is (1) who is leaking and (2) why. Given the nature and timing, there's arguably more onus on journalists to be publicly asking those questions

Anyway, I just think journalism - both the stories and the job - is ultimately about people and I think you lose something pretty significant by not being around them very often.

I remember my first ever death knock: a young woman who'd in a car crash. Ahead of the interview I was terrified. Afterwards the snapper who I was with took me aside and said how well he thought I'd handled it. That small thing set me up for all the others I ended up doing

A few people have mentioned the benefits of being around news editors and subs, as well as other reporters, and I'd definitely agree. I'd also mention photographers. Got a lot from going on jobs with them

@SamMunnery Definitely. For me it was less about directly being given advice and more about watching how more experienced reporters did the job day in, day out. And competition was a big part of it too (for me at least). Seeing others do well and wanting to match them
And it also makes me wonder how relevant my advice really is anymore. Surely they'd be better off hearing from someone who has excelled in that environment.

I know it's not just about where reporters work from. How they do the job has obviously changed too. I'm not lamenting the focus on digital, at least not here. But I do think the two things combined make it a uniquely tricky time to be starting out in journalism
@JustaScribbler Definitely

Over the last six months I've been mentoring reporters who started their careers just before or during the pandemic. They're no different in many ways from the trainees I worked with ten years ago, but the experience they've had in their first 12-18 months has been far narrower

It's unlikely someone starting their first job in local media now would find themselves in that environment, and I do think that's a shame. There are plenty of things you can't learn on a course, and I don't think WFH is an ideal way to begin a journalism career

I think you don't realise enough at the time how much you learn, indirectly and directly, from being in that environment and seeing other people do the job, as well as the benefits of being part of a team and the competitive nature of a newsroom

While things were far from perfect when I started in 2008, a trainee reporter could still generally expect to start his or her career in a newsroom surrounded by other reporters, some with decades of experience
Speaking to @GoldsmithsUoL students on Thursday about how to find stories. Updating my presentation and reflecting on just how challenging a time it is to start a career in journalism

Thurrock is - ridiculously enough - allowed to borrow hundreds of millions from a publicly-funded lending body for the sole purpose of propping up this ailing business model https://t.co/n0oiTHwQrE

So if you're going to write about the council's current budget issues, you really ought to accurately report the very pertinent background (and in more depth than just 'oh and they borrowed ¬£1bn...')
